Red Wine Quality: Exploration Data Analysis

by Shaswati Ghosh

Below analysis is done to find the relation between ‘Quality’ of red wine and other parameters. The data set is containing 1,599 red wines with 11 chemical properties of the wine. The quality rating is between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).

To get the correlation matrix, we need a proper subset of columns. The first column does not have any name, hence first assigning a name to it and then creating a subset removing first and last column(this is newly added factor for quality value). Then populating the correlation table.

Let’s look at the visual representation of the correlations using Scatter plot.

Correlation Matrix plot

Both the table and matrix shows that, the strongest correlations with QUALITY occurs with ALCOHOL percentage and VOLATILE ACIDITY. Correlation coefficients are 0.476 and -0.391 respectively. Now this VOLATILE ACIDITY has strong correaltion with CITRIC ACID(-0.55). And this last one has strongest correaltion with FIXED ACIDITY and pH. The correlation of pH with ‘volatile.acidity’ and ‘citric.acid’ is similar and always negative. We will check multi variable dependency in next section. Here by , will check dependency of QUALITY on each of the variable using box-plot first.

Box Plots

Boxplot distribution supports the fact that, higher quality wine has high ALCOHOL percentage and high SULPHATES amount. To get a better view of SULPHATES one, limiting the Y-axis.

This shows the increase of SULPHATES with better quality. Other plots are as below.

pH has decreasing value with increase in QUALITY. Here we can see some interesting distribution for TOTAL.SULFUR.DIOXIDE. Amount of ‘Total So2’ is higher for wine quality of 5 and 6, Where as the same is less for both the lower and higher quality than the middle one.

Free SO2 is also having almost same distribution as ‘Total SO2’. As the quality moves to both the extreme end, i.e. to either very low or very high, ‘Free SO2’ has decreased value compared to medium quality(4,5,6,7) wine.

Chlorides has decreasing amount as the wine quality increases. For quality 8, most of them are below mean value.

Y axis has been cut down to get a better and closure view for RESIDUAL.SUGAR. We can see that his variable has no specific effect on wine quality. But for CITRIC.ACID has a very prominant influence on wine QUALITY. Increase in wine quality shows good amount of increase in ‘Citric Acid’.

VOLATILE.ACIDITY has decreasing value with increase in wine quality and the relation is strong enough. FIXED.ACIDITY does not show any specific effect on wine QUALITY at this plot.

Higher quality wine has little less DENSITY.

After analysing the above plots, we can say that some of them are having positove relationship and some of them are having negative relationship with quality. ‘Alcohol’, ‘Citric Acid’ shows some strong increasing relation with quality. ‘Sulphates’. ‘Fixed Acidity’ also shows increasing value with better quality, but not too prominent. ‘pH’. ‘Chlorides’,‘Volatile Acidity’, ‘Density’ have decreasing value with increasing quality. ‘Total SO2’, ‘Free SO2’ have higher value for middle range and lower balue for both low and high quality wine. ‘Residual Sugar’ is not showing any significant effect on quality determination.

These plots shows that, if we further categories wine quality, we can have a more clear view. Now we will see the distribution against QUALITY.CAT

Final Plots

Plot 1: Alcohol and Volatile Acidity with Quality

The box plots shows variation of ‘alcohol’ percentage and ‘volatile acid’ amount with the increase in wine quality. Alcohol is the characteristic that increases a perceived quality of wine the most and volatile acidity, on the contrary, reduce a perceived quality the most. This is suported by the correlation table value which shows positive correlation coefficient for alcohol and negative for ‘volatile acid’. The sctter pplot also indicate the same thing, higher quality wine are located on the upper left side of the plot, which denotes the higher value of ‘Alcohol’ and lower value of ‘Volatile.Acidity’.

Plot 2: Free SO2 and Total SO2 with Quality

The amount of ‘free sulfur dioxide’ and ‘total sulfur dioxide’ vary greatly for the given sample data, from 1 to 72 for ‘free SO2’ and from 6 to 289 for ‘total SO2’. These are huge range. Use of SO2 in wine is a concern for health related issues. Correlation table shows that ‘free SO2’ and ‘total SO2’ both have very low negative correlation coeffeciant with wine ‘quality’. Above box plots shows some interesting influence on wine quality. Their value is higher for medium category(5,6) and lower for both the other two category. They do not have any directional influence on wine quality, but their value is low for high quality wine.

Plot 3: Sulphate and Alcohol VS Quality

‘Sulphates’ has a positive correlation coefficient of 0.3 with wine quality. After ‘alcohol’ and ‘volatile acidity’, this is the next influential ingredient to determine the wine quality as per correlation table. Both ‘alcohol’ and ‘sulphates’ increasing value with increase in wine quality.
Higher quality wine is on the upper right side, which denotes high value of both ‘Alcohol’ and ‘Sulphates’. Combination of these two variables are doing big part it determining the quality.

Reflections

Given data set has information on 1,599 different red wines.Primary goal of this analysis is to find which chemical properties affect wine quality most. To understand the characteristics of all variables,firsted I started by exploring the individual distributions of each variables. To furthr know the dependency and relation with each other, then calculated and plotted the correlation matrix. Then I have tried to find out relation between quality and the variables. Very few orrelations are above 0.7. Among all of them, alcohol percentage and volatile acidity have shown relatively strong correlations with quality. Then tried to visualize the multivariate plot to extablish the relation found in bivariate analysis. Alcohol is the characteristic that increasees a perceived quality of wine the most and volatile acidity, on the contrary, reduce a perceived quality the most. As per data source, the sample is of the Portuguese “Vinho Verde” wine. It would be good to have dataset of different regions to have a broader view of the investigation. To do further investigation, price can be included as parameter in the data set as well. After doing some Google search, came to know that storage time and storage method are also some influencing factor for wine quality. So these information can also be inculded in future investigation. Another interesting analysis can be done by comparing red wine with white wine.
